SIMPLE: exercise
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exercise
<hw>Ex"er*cise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>exercice</ets>, L. <ets>exercitium</ets>, from <ets>exercere</ets>,
<ets>exercitum</ets>, to drive on, keep, busy, prob. orig., to thrust or
drive out of the inclosure; <ets>ex</ets> out + <ets>arcere</ets> to
shut up, inclose. See <er>Ark</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
exercising; a setting in action or practicing; employment in the proper
mode of activity; exertion; application; use; habitual activity;
occupation, in general; practice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>exercise of the important function confided by the constitution to
the legislature.</q> <rj><qau>Jefferson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O we will walk this world,⟦br⟧
Yoked in all <qex>exercise</qex> of noble end.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Exertion for the sake of training or improvement
whether physical, intellectual, or moral; practice to acquire skill,
knowledge, virtue, perfectness, grace, etc.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Desire of
knightly <xex>exercise</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An <qex>exercise</qex> of the eyes and memory.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Bodily exertion for the sake of keeping the organs
and functions in a healthy state; hygienic activity; <as>as, to take
<ex>exercise</ex> on horseback; to <ex>exercise</ex> on a treadmill or
in a gym</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wise for cure on <qex>exercise</qex> depend.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The performance of an office, a ceremony, or a
religious duty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lewis refused even those of the church of England . . . the public
<qex>exercise</qex> of their religion.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To draw him from his holy <qex>exercise</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>That which is done for the sake of exercising,
practicing, training, or promoting skill, health, mental, improvement,
moral discipline, etc.; that which is assigned or prescribed for such
ends; hence, a disquisition; a lesson; a task; <as>as, military or naval
<ex>exercises</ex>; musical <ex>exercises</ex>; an <ex>exercise</ex> in
composition; arithmetic <ex>exercises</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The clumsy <qex>exercises</qex> of the European tourney.</q>
<rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He seems to have taken a degree, and performed public
<qex>exercises</qex> in Cambridge, in 1565.</q>
<rj><qau>Brydges.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>That which gives practice; a trial; a
test.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Patience is more oft the <qex>exercise</qex>⟦br⟧
Of saints, the trial of their fortitude.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Exercise bone</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a deposit
of bony matter in the soft tissues, produced by pressure or
exertion.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 524 --></p>

<p><ent>Exercise</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Exercise
<hw>Ex"er*cise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Exercised</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Exercising</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To set in action; to cause to act, move, or make exertion; to give
employment to; to put in action habitually or constantly; to school or
train; to exert repeatedly; to busy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Herein do I <qex>Exercise</qex> myself, to have always a
conscience void of offence.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xxiv. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To exert for the sake of training or improvement; to
practice in order to develop; hence, also, to improve by practice; to
discipline, and to use or to for the purpose of training; <as>as, to
<ex>exercise</ex> arms; to <ex>exercise</ex> one's self in music; to
<ex>exercise</ex> troops.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>About him <qex>exercised</qex> heroic games⟦br⟧
The unarmed youth.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To occupy the attention and effort of; to task; to
tax, especially in a painful or vexatious manner; harass; to vex; to
worry or make anxious; to affect; to discipline; <as>as,
<ex>exercised</ex> with pain</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where pain of unextinguishable fire⟦br⟧
Must <qex>exercise</qex> us without hope of end.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To put in practice; to carry out in action; to
perform the duties of; to use; to employ; to practice; <as>as, to
<ex>exercise</ex> authority; to <ex>exercise</ex> an
office.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am the Lord which <qex>exercise</qex> loving-kindness, judgment,
and righteousness in the earth.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. ix. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The people of the land have used oppression and
<qex>exercised</qex> robbery.</q> <rj><qau>Ezek. xxii.
29.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exercise</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Exercise
<hw>Ex"er*cise</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To exercise one's self, as
under military training; to drill; to take exercise; to use action or
exertion; to practice gymnastics; <as>as, to <ex>exercise</ex> for
health or amusement</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I wear my trusty sword,⟦br⟧
When I do <qex>exercise</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>exerciser</ent>⟦br⟧
